WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:14.140
The Bottle Imp by Robert Louis Stevenson

00:14.140 --> 00:16.500
Copyright Black Cat Publishing

00:31.000 --> 00:40.000
Robert Louis Stevenson was born in Edinburgh, Scotland, in November 1850.

00:40.000 --> 00:47.000
When he was a child, his father told him stories of pirates and adventures.

00:47.000 --> 00:51.000
Robert liked these stories very much.

00:51.000 --> 00:58.000
When he went to university, he first studied engineering, but he did not like it,

00:58.000 --> 01:01.000
so he decided to study law.

01:01.000 --> 01:08.000
But he never worked as a lawyer, because his dream was to become a writer.

01:08.000 --> 01:11.000
And his dream came true.

01:11.000 --> 01:19.000
He became a popular writer and wrote novels, short stories, and poems.

01:19.000 --> 01:22.000
He wrote a lot of stories.

01:23.000 --> 01:28.000
Many of them are adventures and fantasy stories.

01:28.000 --> 01:32.000
He is very popular as a writer of children's stories.

01:32.000 --> 01:43.000
Because he wrote famous stories such as Treasure Island, 1883, and Kidnart, 1886.

01:44.000 --> 01:52.000
Another very famous children's classic is the Black Arrow 1888.

01:52.000 --> 02:02.000
His great success was the strange case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde, 1886.

02:02.000 --> 02:07.000
It is the story of a doctor and a drug he discovers.

02:07.000 --> 02:13.000
This changes him from a good person into a monster.

02:13.000 --> 02:18.000
Stevenson suffered from tuberculosis and was often ill.

02:18.000 --> 02:24.000
Scotland is a cold and wet country, and this did not help him.

02:24.000 --> 02:32.000
So he decided to leave Scotland and travel to Spain and France, because there was warm weather.

02:32.000 --> 02:36.000
His first books describe his time there.

02:36.000 --> 02:45.000
During a trip in California in 1876, he met an American woman, Fanny Osborne.

02:45.000 --> 02:51.000
He fell in love with her, but she was already married.

02:51.000 --> 03:01.000
In 1879, Fanny Osborne divorced her husband, and in 1880 she married Stevenson.

03:02.000 --> 03:08.000
In 1888, they decided to go to the South Seas.

03:08.000 --> 03:16.000
They visited many islands in the Pacific, including Tahiti, Samoa, and Hawaii.

03:16.000 --> 03:23.000
They enjoyed this trip very much, and decided to move to the island of Samoa.

03:23.000 --> 03:27.000
Stevenson continued to write many stories.

03:27.000 --> 03:35.000
In 1891, inspired by his visit to Hawaii, he wrote The Bottle Imp.

03:35.000 --> 03:45.000
In 1893, he published this story in a collection of eight stories called Island Nights Entertainment.

03:45.000 --> 03:50.000
All of these stories were about the islands in the Pacific.

03:50.000 --> 03:57.000
Robert Louis Stevenson died in Samoa on the 3rd of December, 1894.

03:57.000 --> 04:00.000
He was 44 years old.

04:00.000 --> 04:07.000
The islanders decided to bury him on Mount Vahir.

04:11.000 --> 04:14.000
Listening activity.

04:14.000 --> 04:17.000
A

04:18.000 --> 04:20.000
A sailor works on a boat.

04:23.000 --> 04:24.000
B

04:26.000 --> 04:30.000
Passengers and objects can travel on a ship.

04:33.000 --> 04:34.000
C

04:36.000 --> 04:40.000
You can keep clothes and other objects in a chest.

04:43.000 --> 04:44.000
D

04:45.000 --> 04:49.000
A pocket is sometimes part of your clothing.

04:49.000 --> 04:52.000
You can carry things here.

04:55.000 --> 04:56.000
E

04:57.000 --> 05:02.000
A coin is a small round piece of metal used as money.

05:05.000 --> 05:06.000
F

05:07.000 --> 05:11.000
A bottle is a glass or plastic container.

05:14.000 --> 05:15.000
G

05:17.000 --> 05:22.000
A hill isn't a mountain, but it is very high.

05:24.000 --> 05:25.000
H

05:26.000 --> 05:32.000
A harbor is an area near the coast, and you can leave your boat there.

05:33.000 --> 05:34.000
I

05:36.000 --> 05:40.000
An imp is a small creature with magical powers.

05:45.000 --> 05:48.000
Chapter 1

05:48.000 --> 05:50.000
A strange meeting.

05:52.000 --> 05:56.000
Ki-Awe was a courageous but poor man from Hawaii.

05:57.000 --> 06:01.000
His real name is secret because he is still alive.

06:02.000 --> 06:06.000
He could read and write, and he was an excellent sailor.

06:07.000 --> 06:11.000
One day he decided to go and see the world.

06:12.000 --> 06:15.000
So he went on a ship to San Francisco.

06:16.000 --> 06:21.000
The city was beautiful with a lovely harbor, and there were many rich people.

06:23.000 --> 06:26.000
One day Ki-Awe went for a walk on a hill.

06:27.000 --> 06:29.000
There were some beautiful houses.

06:30.000 --> 06:31.000
He looked at them and thought.

06:32.000 --> 06:34.000
These houses are nice.

06:34.000 --> 06:36.000
The people must be very happy.

06:37.000 --> 06:41.000
They are rich, so they don't worry about the future.

06:42.000 --> 06:45.000
He arrived at a small but lovely house.

06:46.000 --> 06:48.000
A man looked out of a window.

06:49.000 --> 06:53.000
Ki-Awe looked at him, and the man looked at Ki-Awe too.

06:54.000 --> 06:55.000
The man was old.

06:56.000 --> 06:59.000
He was bald and had a long black beard.

07:00.000 --> 07:02.000
He seemed to be very unhappy.

07:03.000 --> 07:07.000
Ki-Awe was envious of the man because he had a beautiful house.

07:08.000 --> 07:12.000
But the old man was also envious of Ki-Awe.

07:13.000 --> 07:15.000
Suddenly the old man said,

07:16.000 --> 07:18.000
Come and see my house.

07:19.000 --> 07:24.000
He showed Ki-Awe every room, and Ki-Awe was very surprised.

07:25.000 --> 07:26.000
The house was perfect.

07:27.000 --> 07:30.000
You live in a beautiful house.

07:31.000 --> 07:33.000
Why are you so sad?

07:33.000 --> 07:34.000
Ask Ki-Awe.

07:35.000 --> 07:38.000
You can have a house like this.

07:39.000 --> 07:40.000
Do you have any money?

07:41.000 --> 07:42.000
Ask the old man.

07:43.000 --> 07:46.000
Ki-Awe shook his head sadly and said,

07:47.000 --> 07:52.000
I only have $50, so I can't buy a beautiful house like this.

07:54.000 --> 07:57.000
I am sorry you do not have much money.

07:58.000 --> 07:59.000
So take this.

08:00.000 --> 08:02.000
It is yours for $50.

08:03.000 --> 08:04.000
The house.

08:05.000 --> 08:06.000
Asked Ki-Awe surprised?

08:07.000 --> 08:09.000
No. The bottle.

08:10.000 --> 08:15.000
Because all I have comes from this small bottle.

08:22.000 --> 08:23.000
Listening activity.

08:24.000 --> 08:26.000
What is an imp?

08:27.000 --> 08:30.000
An imp is a type of genie.

08:31.000 --> 08:36.000
It is usually a sleep and prisoner inside a bottle or a lamp.

08:37.000 --> 08:44.000
When somebody wakes it up, the imp must serve this person with its magical powers.

08:45.000 --> 08:48.000
And sometimes make their wishes come true.

08:49.000 --> 08:52.000
An imp can be good or evil.

08:54.000 --> 08:58.000
Usually bad imps play horrible jokes on people.

09:00.000 --> 09:05.000
You can read about a famous genie in 1001 Nights.

09:06.000 --> 09:10.000
A boy, a lad-in, finds a magic oil lamp,

09:11.000 --> 09:13.000
but he does not know there is a genie inside.

09:14.000 --> 09:19.000
Suddenly it comes out of the lamp and gives him three wishes.

09:24.000 --> 09:29.000
Chapter 2. The Bottle Imp

09:30.000 --> 09:35.000
The old man showed Ki-Awe around bottle with a long neck.

09:36.000 --> 09:40.000
It was white, but there were also many different colors.

09:41.000 --> 09:43.000
The colors of the rainbow.

09:44.000 --> 09:46.000
Ki-Awe looked at it closely.

09:47.000 --> 09:51.000
He saw the colors change and he saw something inside move.

09:52.000 --> 09:54.000
The old man said.

09:55.000 --> 09:59.000
You can't break this bottle because it is magic.

10:00.000 --> 10:05.000
It comes from hell and inside there is an imp.

10:06.000 --> 10:08.000
This imp is very powerful.

10:09.000 --> 10:12.000
You can have everything you want.

10:13.000 --> 10:20.000
Love, money, Napoleon and Captain Cook bought it and they became powerful.

10:21.000 --> 10:23.000
So why do you want to sell it?

10:24.000 --> 10:25.000
Asked Ki-Awe.

10:26.000 --> 10:29.000
The imp cannot make me live for a long time.

10:30.000 --> 10:38.000
I am old and I must sell it before I die because I don't want to burn in hell forever.

10:39.000 --> 10:43.000
Well, I don't want to burn in hell, so I won't buy it.

10:44.000 --> 10:45.000
Said Ki-Awe.

10:46.000 --> 10:49.000
You can buy the bottle and then sell it one day.

10:50.000 --> 10:51.000
You can be very happy.

10:52.000 --> 10:53.000
Said the old man.

10:54.000 --> 10:56.000
Ki-Awe was confused.

10:57.000 --> 11:00.000
There are two things that I can't understand.

11:01.000 --> 11:05.000
The bottle can make you happy, but you are very sad.

11:06.000 --> 11:11.000
And the bottle can make you powerful, but it is very cheap.

11:12.000 --> 11:13.000
The old man said.

11:14.000 --> 11:21.000
I am sad because I am old and ill and I must sell this bottle before I die.

11:22.000 --> 11:30.000
In the past, the bottle was very expensive, but every time someone sells it, the price must go down.

11:31.000 --> 11:36.000
You cannot sell the bottle for more money or for the same amount of money.

11:37.000 --> 11:39.000
It always returns to you.

11:40.000 --> 11:43.000
Also, you must pay with coins.

11:44.000 --> 11:46.000
People do not believe you because it is so cheap.

11:48.000 --> 11:49.000
Why don't you try it?

11:50.000 --> 11:52.000
Give me your $50 and make a wish.

11:53.000 --> 11:54.000
Wish for another $50.

11:56.000 --> 12:00.000
So Ki-Awe gave the old man the money and wished for $50.

12:02.000 --> 12:05.000
Immediately, there was another $50 in his pocket.

12:06.000 --> 12:13.000
Ki-Awe was very surprised, but he was also afraid and didn't want to keep the bottle.

12:14.000 --> 12:15.000
The old man said.

12:16.000 --> 12:17.000
It is yours now.

12:18.000 --> 12:19.000
Goodbye.

12:25.000 --> 12:26.000
Captain Cook.

12:28.000 --> 12:34.000
Captain James Cook was a very famous British explorer, navigator.

12:35.000 --> 12:36.000
And cartographer.

12:37.000 --> 12:40.000
He was also an astronomer and a mathematician.

12:42.000 --> 12:48.000
He was born in 1728 in Yorkshire, in the north east of England.

12:49.000 --> 12:53.000
He went to the local school and then he worked on a farm.

12:54.000 --> 12:59.000
In 1755, a war started between England and France.

13:00.000 --> 13:04.000
This war didn't finish until 1763.

13:06.000 --> 13:14.000
Cook decided to enter the Royal Navy and took part in several expeditions in Canada and the Pacific Ocean.

13:15.000 --> 13:17.000
He became an expert cartographer.

13:19.000 --> 13:24.000
After the war, the British government asked Cook to explore the Pacific.

13:25.000 --> 13:28.000
This was Cook's first voyage.

13:29.000 --> 13:35.000
In 1768, he left Plymouth in a single ship, the Endeavour.

13:36.000 --> 13:43.000
Between 1768 and 1771, he explored Tahiti and New Zealand.

13:44.000 --> 13:49.000
At that time, people believed there was a southern continent in the Pacific Ocean.

13:50.000 --> 13:56.000
And during his voyages, Captain Cook's secret mission was to find it.

13:57.000 --> 14:03.000
In 1770, he was successful and found Australia.

14:04.000 --> 14:07.000
He explored and chartered its east coast.

14:08.000 --> 14:12.000
He claimed this area of land for King George III of England.

14:13.000 --> 14:17.000
He also gave it a name, New South Wales.

14:20.000 --> 14:24.000
Captain Cook was an intelligent man with a strong personality.

14:26.000 --> 14:30.000
At that time, many sailors died during the voyages.

14:31.000 --> 14:38.000
He introduced some rules of personal hygiene, and he and his men ate many vegetables and fruit.

14:39.000 --> 14:42.000
As a result, less sailors died.

14:44.000 --> 14:55.000
On his second voyage, between 1772 and 1775, he was the first person to go around Antarctica and the globe from west to east.

14:57.000 --> 15:01.000
This was a very difficult voyage because of the cold weather.

15:02.000 --> 15:10.000
Cook and his men spent the winter months in New Zealand and Tahiti and the summer months exploring the Antarctic.

15:11.000 --> 15:20.000
He discovered many islands, including a group of 15 islands in the South Pacific between Hawaii and New Zealand.

15:21.000 --> 15:25.000
He called these islands the Cook Islands.

15:26.000 --> 15:35.000
On his third expedition to the Pacific Ocean in 1778, he discovered and explored the Hawaiian Islands.

15:36.000 --> 15:39.000
He called them the Sandwich Islands.

15:40.000 --> 15:43.000
His patron was the Earl of Sandwich.

15:44.000 --> 15:53.000
He also tried to find a new route to the East Indies, a northwest passage around Canada and Alaska.

15:54.000 --> 15:57.000
But this time, he was not successful.

15:58.000 --> 16:09.000
During this voyage, he found a lot of ice, and so he decided to return to Hawaii for the winter and find food and drink for his next voyage.

16:10.000 --> 16:16.000
At first, he had a good relationship with the natives of Hawaii, and they were friendly.

16:17.000 --> 16:24.000
But then, things changed, and they killed him in 1779.

16:29.000 --> 16:34.000
Chapter 3, Ki-Awe's Wish Comes True

16:35.000 --> 16:42.000
At first, Ki-Awe thought the bottle wasn't really magical, so he left it in the middle of the road.

16:43.000 --> 16:48.000
But when he turned the corner, the bottle was once again in his pocket.

16:49.000 --> 16:55.000
Then he bought a corkscrew and tried to open the bottle, but it was impossible.

16:56.000 --> 16:59.000
He suddenly became very afraid.

17:00.000 --> 17:08.000
He went into a shop and sold it for $60, but later he found the bottle in his chest.

17:09.000 --> 17:15.000
Ki-Awe told his good friend Lopaka, the story, and asked him to keep it a secret.

17:16.000 --> 17:18.000
Lopaka told him,

17:18.000 --> 17:22.000
I am afraid this bottle will give you problems.

17:23.000 --> 17:29.000
Decide what you want from it, and then sell it to me, because I have a project.

17:30.000 --> 17:37.000
I want a sailing ship so that I can travel and buy and sell many objects on the islands.

17:38.000 --> 17:41.000
Ki-Awe thought for a moment and then said,

17:42.000 --> 17:46.000
My dream is to have a beautiful house in Hawaii.

17:47.000 --> 17:50.000
I want to be happy there with my family and friends.

17:51.000 --> 17:55.000
So Ki-Awe and Lopaka decided to go to Hawaii.

17:56.000 --> 18:01.000
When they arrived, an old friend met them and said to Ki-Awe,

18:02.000 --> 18:07.000
I am very sorry, but your uncle and cousin died while you were away.

18:08.000 --> 18:10.000
Ki-Awe was very sad.

18:11.000 --> 18:13.000
Lopaka told his friend,

18:14.000 --> 18:20.000
Your uncle's land is yours now, and you can build the house of your dreams.

18:21.000 --> 18:24.000
But Ki-Awe was very unhappy.

18:25.000 --> 18:27.000
Did the imp kill his relatives?

18:29.000 --> 18:32.000
Ki-Awe and Lopaka went to see a lawyer.

18:33.000 --> 18:38.000
Ki-Awe discovered that his uncle was very rich and he now had a lot of money.

18:39.000 --> 18:45.000
The lawyer told them about a brilliant new architect, so they went to see him.

18:46.000 --> 18:51.000
When they arrived, the architect already had a drawing of a house on his table.

18:52.000 --> 18:54.000
Ki-Awe was surprised.

18:55.000 --> 18:56.000
It was perfect.

18:57.000 --> 18:59.000
It was the house of his dreams.

19:00.000 --> 19:05.000
The architect wanted exactly the same amount of money that Ki-Awe received from his uncle.

19:07.000 --> 19:12.000
Ki-Awe said it was his destiny to have this house and signed a contract.

19:13.000 --> 19:16.000
But he also thought about the old man's words.

19:17.000 --> 19:19.000
It comes from hell.

19:21.000 --> 19:27.000
Ki-Awe decided not to make any more wishes, and he and Lopaka left for Australia.

19:28.000 --> 19:31.000
They wanted to return when the house was ready.

19:38.000 --> 19:39.000
Chapter 4

19:40.000 --> 19:42.000
Ki-Awe sells the bottle.

19:44.000 --> 19:50.000
When they returned to Hawaii, the house was ready, and it was exactly what Ki-Awe wanted.

19:51.000 --> 19:57.000
The rooms, the furniture, the ornaments, the garden, everything was beautiful.

19:58.000 --> 19:59.000
Lopaka said,

20:00.000 --> 20:04.000
It is possible that the imp has nothing to do with this.

20:05.000 --> 20:12.000
I promise to buy the bottle from you, but before I do, I want to be sure that it really has power.

20:13.000 --> 20:14.000
Ki-Awe replied,

20:15.000 --> 20:17.000
I can't ask the imp for another wish.

20:18.000 --> 20:19.000
I promised.

20:20.000 --> 20:22.000
I only want to see the imp.

20:22.000 --> 20:23.000
Said Lopaka.

20:24.000 --> 20:26.000
Then I will buy the bottle from you.

20:27.000 --> 20:31.000
Ki-Awe was afraid, but he was all so curious.

20:32.000 --> 20:35.000
So he ordered the imp to come out of the bottle.

20:36.000 --> 20:37.000
Come out now.

20:38.000 --> 20:43.000
The imp looked out, but disappeared inside again immediately.

20:45.000 --> 20:49.000
Ki-Awe and Lopaka were very shocked and terrified.

20:50.000 --> 20:52.000
They could not move or speak for hours.

20:53.000 --> 20:55.000
Finally Lopaka said,

20:56.000 --> 20:57.000
I want to keep my promise.

20:58.000 --> 20:59.000
So here is the money.

21:00.000 --> 21:05.000
I will buy my ship, and then I will sell this bottle as soon as possible.

21:06.000 --> 21:07.000
Ki-Awe said,

21:08.000 --> 21:10.000
It is night, and the roads are bad.

21:11.000 --> 21:15.000
But I can't sleep, eat or pray with this bottle in my house.

21:16.000 --> 21:20.000
So please take what you want from my house and leave now.

21:22.000 --> 21:26.000
Lopaka was afraid too, but he understood his friend.

21:27.000 --> 21:29.000
He wished Ki-Awe good luck and left.

21:31.000 --> 21:34.000
As Ki-Awe watched his friend leave, he prayed for him.

21:35.000 --> 21:39.000
But he was also very happy that he didn't have the bottle.

21:41.000 --> 21:45.000
Ki-Awe loved his house, and many people came to visit and admire it.

21:46.000 --> 21:49.000
One day he saw a beautiful girl swimming in the sea.

21:50.000 --> 21:52.000
He immediately fell in love with her.

21:53.000 --> 21:54.000
Her name was Kakua.

21:55.000 --> 21:59.000
He did not tell her his name, because he did not want her to know he was rich.

22:01.000 --> 22:02.000
She took him to her father's house.

22:04.000 --> 22:06.000
Ki-Awe, her father, knew Ki-Awe,

22:07.000 --> 22:11.000
and the girl understood that he was very rich and that he wanted to marry her.

22:18.000 --> 22:19.000
Listening activity.

22:21.000 --> 22:23.000
Hello, Kakua. It's Ki-Awe.

22:24.000 --> 22:26.000
Hello, Ki-Awe. How are you?

22:27.000 --> 22:31.000
Fine, thanks. I'm calling because I want to invite you to a concert.

22:32.000 --> 22:35.000
I have two tickets for the Hawaii Flower Band concert.

22:36.000 --> 22:39.000
Great! I love their music. When is it?

22:40.000 --> 22:42.000
On Saturday afternoon, at 6.15.

22:43.000 --> 22:45.000
Fine. When can we meet?

22:46.000 --> 22:49.000
We can meet at 5.30. Is that okay?

22:50.000 --> 22:52.000
Of course. Where is the concert?

22:53.000 --> 22:59.000
It's at the Hawaiian Arena. We can meet at the entrance. Do you know the address?

23:00.000 --> 23:01.000
No, I don't.

23:02.000 --> 23:04.000
It's 14 Gogan Road.

23:04.000 --> 23:06.000
How do you spell that?

23:07.000 --> 23:16.000
G-A-U-G-U-I-N.

23:17.000 --> 23:18.000
What can I wear?

23:19.000 --> 23:25.000
Casual clothes are okay. Just put on a pair of jeans. They are comfortable.

23:26.000 --> 23:29.000
Great. See you there then. Bye.

23:30.000 --> 23:31.000
Bye.

23:35.000 --> 23:37.000
Hawaii.

23:39.000 --> 23:48.000
The Hawaiian Islands are in the Pacific Ocean, about 2,500 miles west of San Francisco.

23:49.000 --> 23:55.000
They became part of the United States on the 21st of August, 1959.

23:56.000 --> 24:05.000
They are the 50th state of the United States and consist of 8 big islands and over 100 small ones.

24:06.000 --> 24:10.000
Most of the population live on 6 islands.

24:11.000 --> 24:19.000
Hawaii, Kauai, Lanai, Maui, Molokai and Oahu.

24:19.000 --> 24:20.000
Oahu.

24:23.000 --> 24:24.000
Some history.

24:26.000 --> 24:32.000
From the 16th century, people from Tahiti and the Marquesas Islands occupied this land.

24:33.000 --> 24:40.000
The first European to discover these islands was Captain Cook in 1778.

24:41.000 --> 24:47.000
At the beginning of the 19th century, missionaries, tradesmen and whale hunters

24:47.000 --> 24:50.000
arrived from England and the USA.

24:51.000 --> 25:00.000
Unfortunately, they also brought many new diseases and consequently 80% of the native population died.

25:01.000 --> 25:09.000
Later, these islands became very important for their production of sugar cane and many immigrants arrived.

25:10.000 --> 25:18.000
In 1941, the Japanese attacked the famous Pearl Harbor U.S. military base on the Oahu island

25:18.000 --> 25:23.000
and the USA entered the Second World War as a result.

25:25.000 --> 25:27.000
Hawaii Today

25:28.000 --> 25:36.000
Today, the main economic activities of these islands are tourism and the growing of sugar cane and pineapples.

25:37.000 --> 25:41.000
The capital of the state is Honolulu on the Oahu island.

25:42.000 --> 25:45.000
This island has the most tourists.

25:46.000 --> 25:56.000
On their arrival, the tourists can relax on the many wonderful beaches of white sand and swim in the incredibly blue water of the ocean.

25:57.000 --> 26:10.000
Some important symbols of Hawaii are hula dances, the lei flowers, grass skirts, ukulele, Hawaiian music.

26:11.000 --> 26:18.000
For surfers, the best island is Maui. Here, there are also spectacular beaches.

26:19.000 --> 26:27.000
The island of Kauai is called the Garden Island. It has many beautiful rivers and waterfalls.

26:28.000 --> 26:38.000
Big Island is the second name of the island of Hawaii. Its capital is called Hilo and the island is famous for its volcanoes.

26:39.000 --> 26:45.000
Particularly famous are Mauna Kea and Kilauea Crater.

26:46.000 --> 26:52.000
Mauna Kea is 4,025 meters high and is a sleeping volcano.

26:52.000 --> 26:56.000
Sometimes you even see some snow at the top.

26:57.000 --> 27:02.000
Kilauea Crater is a very active volcano and erupts regularly.

27:03.000 --> 27:07.000
Luckily, these eruptions are usually very small.

27:09.000 --> 27:14.000
Chapter 5

27:15.000 --> 27:18.000
Kiauea must find the bottle again.

27:19.000 --> 27:24.000
Kiauea was very happy and he sang when he went home.

27:25.000 --> 27:32.000
He sang when he ate his dinner on the balcony and his Chinese servant heard him sing when he prepared his bath.

27:33.000 --> 27:37.000
Suddenly, the singing stopped.

27:38.000 --> 27:48.000
When Kiauea took off his clothes, he saw a mark on his body. He understood immediately. He had leprosy.

27:49.000 --> 27:58.000
In a moment, all his dreams disappeared and he was desperate because he knew it was impossible to marry Kokua.

28:00.000 --> 28:06.000
Then he suddenly thought of the bottle. The bottle could cure his illness.

28:07.000 --> 28:19.000
It was his only possibility. He wanted to marry Kokua very much. He was afraid, but he decided to look for Lopaka.

28:20.000 --> 28:29.000
Somebody told him Lopaka had a big ship, but he was far away. He thought of Lopaka's friends and remembered the lawyer.

28:30.000 --> 28:35.000
He discovered that he was very rich now and had a lovely house on a beach.

28:36.000 --> 28:43.000
When he saw Kiauea, the lawyer seemed worried, but he gave Kiauea the name of another person.

28:44.000 --> 28:49.000
Kiauea met a lot of rich people, but nobody had the bottle.

28:50.000 --> 29:05.000
Finally, one evening, he found a young man. This man was rich like the others, but he looked terrible. His face was white and he had dark rings around his eyes.

29:06.000 --> 29:12.000
Kiauea knew that this was the person. He had the bottle.

29:13.000 --> 29:21.000
Kiauea said, I am here to buy the bottle. The bottle? To buy the bottle? He whispered.

29:22.000 --> 29:31.000
Yes. How much does it cost now? asked Kiauea. The man was shocked and the glass in his hand fell to the floor.

29:32.000 --> 29:41.000
The price? Don't you know the price? I paid two cents for it.

29:42.000 --> 29:51.000
He said, Kiauea answered. So, you can only sell it for one cent and the person who buys it?

29:52.000 --> 30:04.000
He could not finish the sentence. He understood. He could never sell the bottle again. The young man fell on his knees and begged him.

30:05.000 --> 30:11.000
Please buy the bottle. I will give you everything I have.

30:16.000 --> 30:33.000
Chapter 6, a great idea. Kiauea gave the man one cent. He made his wish and then he took the bottle. He looked in a mirror. It was a miracle.

30:34.000 --> 30:47.000
The mark was not there. The problem now was that he did not care about his health or for Kiauea. He thought only about the bottle imp and his destiny.

30:48.000 --> 30:59.000
He was very depressed. Kiauea remembered that there was a concert in town that evening. He decided to go because he did not want to be alone.

31:00.000 --> 31:07.000
Courage returned to him when they played Kiauea's and his song and he decided to return to Hawaii.

31:08.000 --> 31:23.000
He married Kiauea and carried her to his beautiful house. When they were together, he was very happy and calm. But when he was alone, he was always very worried and depressed.

31:24.000 --> 31:35.000
Kiauea loved him very much and brought him much happiness. But Kiauea saw that Kiauea was unhappy and she did not understand.

31:36.000 --> 31:42.000
She thought that she was responsible and decided to ask him. She told him,

31:43.000 --> 31:49.000
Before we married, you were always happy. But now you do not smile anymore.

31:51.000 --> 31:59.000
Kiauea told her his story so she could understand how much he loved her. Kiauea cried and said,

32:00.000 --> 32:01.000
I will save you.

32:02.000 --> 32:04.000
You cannot help me.

32:06.000 --> 32:10.000
He answered sadly. But Kiauea said,

32:11.000 --> 32:15.000
I went to school in Honolulu. I'm not stupid.

32:16.000 --> 32:22.000
There are other countries in the world where people use different money, like in England and France.

32:23.000 --> 32:27.000
For one cent, we can have four French song teams.

32:28.000 --> 32:34.000
Let's go to the French Islands, to Tahiti. We can sell the bottle for some teams.

32:41.000 --> 32:45.000
Chapter 7 Kiauea can't sell the bottle.

32:47.000 --> 32:58.000
Kiauea was very happy and they prepared for the voyage. They took all their best clothes and jewels because they wanted to seem rich.

32:59.000 --> 33:02.000
This was important to sell the bottle imp.

33:03.000 --> 33:09.000
When they arrived, they rented an ice house, a carriage and some horses.

33:10.000 --> 33:15.000
Kiauea was very courageous and used the bottle imp for money.

33:16.000 --> 33:22.000
They learned the local language and when they could speak it, they tried to sell the bottle.

33:23.000 --> 33:30.000
It was very difficult. People didn't think they were honest because the bottle was so cheap.

33:31.000 --> 33:36.000
People avoided them and Kiauea and Kiauea were very depressed.

33:37.000 --> 33:41.000
They could not sleep at night because they were afraid.

33:42.000 --> 33:46.000
One night Kiauea woke up but her husband was not in bed.

33:47.000 --> 33:52.000
She found him under the banana trees, crying silently.

33:53.000 --> 33:56.000
She understood that she must save him.

33:57.000 --> 34:00.000
She left the house and went for a walk.

34:01.000 --> 34:04.000
She saw a poor old man under a tree.

34:05.000 --> 34:07.000
A stranger on the island.

34:08.000 --> 34:10.000
And she told him their story.

34:11.000 --> 34:15.000
She asked him to go to Kiauea and buy the bottle.

34:17.000 --> 34:22.000
Then she wanted to buy the bottle from the old man and save her husband.

34:23.000 --> 34:28.000
So the old man went to Kiauea, bought the bottle and came back.

34:29.000 --> 34:32.000
Your husband cried with happiness.

34:33.000 --> 34:35.000
I am sure he was asleep tonight.

34:36.000 --> 34:37.000
He said.

34:38.000 --> 34:40.000
At first Kiauea hesitated.

34:41.000 --> 34:47.000
But then courage came back to her and she bought the bottle back from him and went home.

34:48.000 --> 34:55.000
Her husband slept like a child but she couldn't sleep or be happy.

34:56.000 --> 34:59.000
When Kiauea woke up, he was very pleased.

35:00.000 --> 35:04.000
He did not notice that Kiauea was sad and could not eat.

35:05.000 --> 35:12.000
He told her the story, thanked her, planned their return home and laughed at the stupid old man.

35:14.000 --> 35:20.000
Kiauea was angry because Kiauea was not happy and he left her alone.

35:21.000 --> 35:28.000
When he came back, he told her she was not a good wife because she was not happy for him.

35:29.000 --> 35:34.000
Kiauea left the house and went out with some friends and they drank a lot.

35:35.000 --> 35:42.000
One of the drinkers, a sailor and an ex-prisoner, was a bad and dishonest person.

35:43.000 --> 35:47.000
He wanted an expensive drink and so he said.

35:48.000 --> 35:55.000
Hey, Kiauea, you are very rich. Bring some money so we can buy some rum.

35:56.000 --> 35:57.000
Kiauea replied.

35:58.000 --> 36:00.000
I'll go home because my wife keeps our money.

36:01.000 --> 36:02.000
The sailor replied.

36:03.000 --> 36:10.000
Don't leave your money with her. You can never trust women. They are all false.

36:11.000 --> 36:17.000
Kiauea started to think this was true because Kiauea was so unhappy.

36:23.000 --> 36:27.000
Chapter 8 A surprising end

36:29.000 --> 36:35.000
When Kiauea went home and opened the door, he saw his wife with the bottle near her.

36:36.000 --> 36:39.000
He was very shocked and did not believe it.

36:40.000 --> 36:47.000
He immediately thought that the bottle was there again because there was an error when he sold it to the old man.

36:48.000 --> 36:51.000
He closed the door and waited for a moment.

36:52.000 --> 36:58.000
Then he opened it again, loudly, but this time the bottle was not there.

36:59.000 --> 37:00.000
He said to Kiauea.

37:01.000 --> 37:06.000
I only want some money because I want to drink some expensive rum with my friends.

37:07.000 --> 37:13.000
He went to his chest and pretended to look for the money, but the bottle wasn't there.

37:14.000 --> 37:20.000
Finally, he understood. He stopped and looked at his wife.

37:21.000 --> 37:28.000
He knew that expression on her face. He was desperate, so he took some money and left the house.

37:29.000 --> 37:31.000
He did not want to drink now.

37:32.000 --> 37:34.000
He went to the bad sailor and said,

37:34.000 --> 37:41.000
My wife has the bottle. We can have money for a drink, but first you must help me.

37:42.000 --> 37:45.000
I must become the owner of that bottle again.

37:46.000 --> 37:56.000
Here are two some teams. Go and buy the bottle from her. Then I will buy it from you, but don't tell her I am sending you.

37:57.000 --> 37:58.000
Then Kiauea said,

37:58.000 --> 38:07.000
When you come out of the house with the bottle, you can make a wish for some money in your pocket or a very good bottle of rum.

38:08.000 --> 38:11.000
You will then understand that this bottle is magic.

38:12.000 --> 38:25.000
So the man left and Kiauea waited for him. His heart was bitter. He waited for a very long time and then finally he heard the man's voice in the dark.

38:25.000 --> 38:34.000
He was very drunk. He had the devil's bottle in his pocket and another bottle in his hand.

38:35.000 --> 38:37.000
Give me the bottle now, said Kiauea.

38:38.000 --> 38:39.000
Hands off!

38:39.000 --> 38:40.000
Cried the sailor.

38:41.000 --> 38:52.000
This is a good bottle. I can't understand how I got it for only two sontines. I certainly will not give it to you for one sontine.

38:53.000 --> 39:02.000
But I can give you some rum. Do you mean you will not sell it? But you will go to hell, said Kiauea.

39:03.000 --> 39:09.000
I am already going to hell and I like this bottle. Go and look for another one.

39:10.000 --> 39:11.000
The bad sailor answered.

39:12.000 --> 39:14.000
Please sell this bottle to me.

39:15.000 --> 39:16.000
Insisted Kiauea.

39:17.000 --> 39:20.000
I don't believe what you say about this bottle.

39:20.000 --> 39:31.000
You thought I was stupid, but now you can see I am not. If you don't want any of this rum, I'll drink it. Good night.

39:32.000 --> 39:49.000
The sailor left and the bottle disappeared from this story with him. Kiauea ran to Kacua very fast. Their joy was great that night and from that moment they lived happily and peacefully in their lovely house.

39:51.000 --> 39:53.000
Listening activity.

39:55.000 --> 40:19.000
Hi Susan. This is Emma. Do you have any ideas for Julia's birthday present? What about a book? Last week I read a really good story. It was called the bottle imp. The author is Robert Louis Stevenson. I know Julia will like it too.

40:20.000 --> 40:33.000
It's not very expensive. I bought it for £3.40. Please meet me outside the bookshop at 4pm tomorrow. You can send me a text message to confirm. See you then.

40:50.000 --> 40:57.000
Thanks for watching.

